and extensor hallucis brevis. These muscles are involved in extending the toes and are located on the top of the foot.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edeep fibular nerve\u003C/strong\u003E innervates the dorsal muscles of the foot, specifically the extensor digitorum brevis and extensor hallucis brevis. This nerve is a branch of the common fibular nerve, which is derived from the sciatic nerve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperficial fibular nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - This nerve primarily innervates the muscles of the lateral compartment of the leg\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETibial division of sciatic nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - This nerve innervates the posterior compartment of the leg and plantar muscles of the foot\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not a recognised nerve in the context of foot innervation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral plantar nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - This nerve innervates some of the intrinsic muscles of the sole of the foot\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The dorsal muscles of the foot are innervated by the deep fibular nerve.","The deep fibular nerve is responsible for innervating the extensor digitorum brevis and extensor hallucis brevis muscles.","The deep fibular nerve is a branch of the common fibular nerve, which itself is a branch of the sciatic nerve."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton.